import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>When you build an AI research lab, the first major hurdle isn't getting it to write math—it's getting it to <em>stop inventing it</em>.</p>

<p>Our initial autonomous pipeline was brilliant but structurally flawed. When given a prompt like "Find a recent arXiv paper on random graphs and extend it," the Architect (a Gemini inference engine) would hallucinate a magnificent, plausible paper—complete with a fake arXiv ID, a beautifully formatted abstract, and a profound-sounding hypothesis.</p>

<p>It was executing the scientific method perfectly in a completely parallel, fictional universe. To build a true <strong>Mathematician in the Box</strong>—a system that contributes to human mathematical literature—we had to sever the hallucination.</p>

<h2>The Fix: The RAG Bridge</h2>

<p>The solution was a strict Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) patch. Instead of prompting the LLM with a blank slate at a creative <code>temperature: 0.7</code>, we wired the Architect directly to our <strong>ArxivLibrarian</strong>, powered by a local LanceDB vector store.</p>

<p>The pipeline now follows a cold, hard protocol:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Query LanceDB</strong>: For a given prompt, the Librarian embeds the query and fetches the top 10 most relevant, actual peer-reviewed papers.</li>
  <li><strong>Stochastic Selection</strong>: It stochastically samples one of the top matches to guarantee diverse starting points across continuous cron runs.</li>
  <li><strong>Hard-Grounding</strong>: The Architect's prompt is completely rewritten to inject the real Title, arXiv ID, and Abstract, accompanied by a strict directive: <em>"Do not invent a new paper. Base your entire analysis strictly on the paper provided above."</em></li>
</ol>
<p>At an icy <code>temperature: 0.1</code>, the Architect behaves less like a sci-fi author and more like a rigorous graduate student.</p>

<h2>The Breakthrough: Escaping the Asymptotic Trap</h2>

<p>Once grounded to reality, the pipeline pulled actual papers like <em>"A limit theorem for small cliques in inhomogeneous random graphs"</em> (arXiv:1903.10570).</p>

<p>The Architect extended the paper's findings on cliques to hypothesize about 4-cycles ($C_4$), predicting specific fluctuation regimes for the $p = 1/\\sqrt{n}$ critical density limit.</p>

<p>The <strong>Explorer</strong> sub-agent spun up Python scripts across 7 domains (computational statistics, random matrix theory, etc.) and empirically found the quantitative predictions to be flawed. The hypothesis was asymptotically false.</p>

<p>Here is where the magic happened. LLMs notoriously struggle to formally prove infinite limits or asymptotic bounds in Lean 4. To solve this, we injected a <strong>Computational Fast-Path Heuristic</strong>: a strict <code>native_decide</code> constraint forcing the Architect to target <em>finite, computable failing bounds</em> instead of general uncomputable limits.</p>

<p>In response to the empirical Python failure, the AI dropped this exact theorem onto the Lean 4 MCTS Prover:</p>

<pre><code class="language-lean">theorem c4_variance_falsification_N64 :
  let n : ℕ := 64 in
  let p : ℚ := 1 / 8 in
  variance_subgraph_count (cycle_graph 4) n (fun (_ _ : Fin 64) => p) &gt; (n ^ 3 : ℚ) / 2
</code></pre>

<p>Look at the numbers: $N = 64$ and $p = 1/8$. The critical density threshold for a 4-cycle is exactly $p = 1/\\sqrt{N}$. The AI explicitly calculated $1/\\sqrt{64} = 1/8$ and hardcoded the exact mathematical boundary condition as a finite test case.</p>

<p>Because it retreated to a finite bound, the MCTS Prover could immediately leverage the <code>norm_num</code> and <code>decide</code> tactics to computationally smash the threshold without needing complex logical induction.</p>

<h2>The Best Part: Meeting "Reviewer 2"</h2>

<p>We ran the pipeline again on a new topic: <em>"Template-Based Graph Clustering"</em> (arXiv:2107.019994). The hypothesis was robustly confirmed empirically by 8 different Python tests.</p>

<p>But when the Architect tried to formalize the findings, every single Lean 4 candidate was brutally shot down by our internal <strong>Red Team</strong> agent.</p>

<p>The Red Team's audit log read like a rejection letter from a top-tier journal:</p>
<ul>
  <li>It literally constructed a custom bipartite counterexample graph $K_{X,Y}$ to mathematically prove one conjecture false.</li>
  <li>It rejected two bounds as "trivial and known", citing standard Cauchy-Schwarz variance minimization.</li>
  <li>It rejected a technically correct theorem because the <em>description</em> oversold the implications of the bound.</li>
</ul>

<p>The pipeline killed its own run because the output wasn't novel, true, and properly scoped.</p>

<h2>The Road Ahead</h2>

<p>Perqed is no longer just a code generator. It is an autonomous, verifiable, neuro-symbolic research lab executing the Scientific Method.</p>

<p>It reads live literature, writes empirical C/Python tests, falsifies its own hypotheses, and translates those exact failing boundaries into formally verified Lean 4 mathematics.</p>

<p>We've added a 30-second DevOps patch so the pipeline automatically generates its own <code>lakefile.lean</code>, runs <code>lake update</code> to pull <code>Mathlib</code>, and bootstraps its environment with zero configuration.</p>

<p>The Mathematician is in the Box. Now we just let it run.</p>
`;
